  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Increasing access to education among vulnerable children in Northern Iraq</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The overall objective of the project is to contribute to increased resilience of highly vulnerable children in Ninewa governorate by ensuring safe and equitable access to education as well as conflict sensitive and culturally appropriate learning. The proposed project aims to enhance the access to education by minor rehabilitation of classrooms, summerisation and provision of appropriate teaching and learning materials. Back to school campaign will raise awareness among parents about the restored access to schools and learning sites. Secondly, the project aims to increase the quality of education by training 240 teachers and education facilitators in conflict sensitive teaching methodologies and minimum standards for emergency education and psychosocial support. 8,000 conflict affected children, both primary and secondary school aged children, will be targeted in order to help them cope with: i) missed years of schools by provision of catch-up classes over the summer ii) trauma, children might suffer as a result of the conflict and life under ISIL, by provision of psychosocial support and non-formal education and iii) effects of the conflict and displacement by provision of life skills education incl. hygiene and health promotion and mine risk awareness. The proposed project thus focuses on addressing the urgent needs identified by both the Education Cluster and PIN&#x2019;s assessments in the newly retaken areas in Ninewa. It further contributes to fulfillment of the objectives laid out in HRP 2017.
The project targets newly retaken areas/returnee areas with high concentration of vulnerable populations as well as areas where new displacement is expected. Under the project, PIN will continue its work in five schools in Nimrod sub-district and provide support to an additional 7 schools in the districts of Al Hamdaniya and Mosul. This project will complement the work of other education actors, while also addressing the gap of support for out of camp children residing in host communities that are particularly vulnerable as the number of IDPs continues to increase with ongoing operations in Western Mosul city.</narrative>
  </description>
